            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63726"><name nymRef="#Ἡρακλείδης">hε̄ρακλείδε̄<unclear>ς</unclear></name> 
                        <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Κλεα_" type="patronymic"><seg part="I">Κλεα</seg></name></persName></persName><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Herakleides, fils de Klea<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Herakleides, son of Klea<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Herakleides, figlio di Klea<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Published by Pugliese Carratelli from a drawing of Oliverio (not given). In fact, <bibl><ptr target="#oliverio1927"/>, p. <citedRange>158</citedRange></bibl> already described the graffito and gave its provenance:
                 a <foreign rend="italic">thesauron</foreign> inside the pronaos of the 2nd-phase Artemision.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
